STARLINK QUIETLY BUILDS THE BIGGEST NETWORK EARTH HAS EVER SEEN

Starlink has now placed roughly 9,400 satellites into orbit, making it the largest satellite constellation ever assembled. 

Nothing else comes close. 

At any moment, thousands of active satellites are circling the planet, delivering broadband to places that traditional infrastructure never reached.

That includes rural towns, offshore vessels, aircraft, disaster zones, and research stations where fiber is impossible and cell towers do not exist. 

For many users, Starlink is not a backup connection. 

It is the first reliable one they have ever had.

The system has already proven its value during natural disasters, wars, and power outages, where ground networks fail first. 

Schools, hospitals, emergency crews, and small businesses now rely on a signal coming straight from orbit.

SpaceX continues launching new satellites every week, steadily upgrading capacity and performance while expanding coverage. 

More launches are planned, but the system is already operating at a scale that would have sounded unrealistic a decade ago.

Either way, not a future concept. 

The network is live, global, and growing, and it is already changing how the world stays connected.

Source: @XFreeze,Celestrak

tweets.text: RT @chazman: I just finished a three day trip as a Captain on the Airbus A321, including an overnight in Austin the same day Robotaxi was s‚Ä¶

retweet.text: I just finished a three day trip as a Captain on the Airbus A321, including an overnight in Austin the same day Robotaxi was spotted testing driverless.  My last day was after seven hours of flight time landing in Orlando around 11 PM, and I still had a 2 1/2 hour drive home to Jacksonville ahead of me.  This is a use case where FSD Supervised has changed how I use my vehicle.  Previously arriving that late would've meant needing an overnight hotel getting a few hours of sleep, waking up and jumping in the car and driving home the next morning. Driving that late at night was just not safe after a long day of work.  With FSD I have no problem getting in the car and letting the Tesla drive me home with my supervision. My reaction time is slower, I'm tired, but that's where this technology really shines. Unsupervised will change the game even more, but for the time being this technology has already changed the way I live and work.  @Tesla_AI
